        <section id="Kankaleshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Kankaleshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="images/beed.jpeg" alt="Kankaleshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Shri Kankaleshwar Temple, located in Beed, Maharashtra, is a revered ancient Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Shiva. While the exact date of its construction remains unknown due to a lack of inscriptions, the temple's architectural style suggests it was likely built between the 10th and 12th centuries, possibly during the Yadava period or by the Chalukya King Vikramaditya VI. The temple's most striking feature is its location in the middle of a square-shaped tank (pond), accessed by a causeway and a flight of steps. Built entirely of black stone, the temple showcases a unique star-shaped architectural style, reminiscent of the Ellora Caves. It features intricate carvings of Hindu gods, goddesses, and human figures, including kirtimukhas. The presence of idols depicting women fighting suggests their active participation in battles during the Chalukya period. The octagonal pavilion is supported by 16 pillars, and the domed roof is adorned with floral carvings.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Khandoba Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Khandoba Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Khandoba Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Khandoba Temple in Beed, though lacking a precise construction date, is believed to be a 17th-century structure, showcasing the Hemadpanti architectural style, according to Wikiwand. Its spire, in the same style, crowns the structure, and the entrance to the sanctum is adorned with an image of Ganesha. While the main idol is missing, a sculpture of a man and woman on horseback remains in the sanctum. According to Wikiwand and other sources, the temple is situated on the eastern hills of Beed and is considered a prominent landmark of the city. Notably, two 45-foot octagonal lamp towers (dipadans) with square bases stand east of the temple, featuring five stories with arched openings and stucco embellishments. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sautada Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Sautada Waterfall</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sautada Waterfall" class="section-image">
            <p>Sautada Waterfall, nestled in the scenic landscapes of Beed, Maharashtra, is a captivating natural wonder boasting both breathtaking beauty and spiritual significance. The Waterfall, also known as the Rameshwar Waterfall, is surrounded by lush greenery, especially vibrant during the monsoon and post-monsoon seasons, offering a refreshing escape from the hustle and bustle of city life. A unique aspect of Sautada Waterfall is the ancient Rameshwar Temple dedicated to Lord Shiva, located nearby, creating a serene and contemplative atmosphere. To reach the temple and waterfall, visitors embark on a descent down 350 steep steps, adding an adventurous element of a mini-hike or trek to the experience. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Khazana Well" class="section">
            <h2>Khazana Well</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Khazana Well" class="section-image">
            <p>The Khazana Well, also known as Khazana Bawadi or Khazana Vihir, is a historical well located in Beed, Maharashtra, India. It is renowned for its consistent water level, even during droughts, and is believed to have been constructed in 1583 by Salabat Khan, a Jagirdar of Beed. The well's design incorporates underground tunnels that collect and distribute water, showcasing the advanced irrigation techniques of the Nizam period. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Majalgaon Dam " class="section">
            <h2>Majalgaon Dam </h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Majalgaon Dam " class="section-image">
            <p>The Majalgaon Dam, located in the Beed district of Maharashtra, India, is an earthfill dam built on the Sindphana River. The dam serves multiple purposes, primarily for irrigation of agricultural land in the Beed, Parbhani, and Nanded districts, but also provides drinking water to Beed city and nearby areas. Additionally, it's a source of hydroelectric power, with three generators, each capable of producing 750 kilowatts. The Majalgaon Dam is a significant component of the Jayakwadi Project Stage II. Construction began in 1977, following approval by the Maharashtra government in 1976, and the dam was opened in 1987. The dam's design features earth berms on either side of a gated concrete spillway situated approximately 2 kilometers upstream from the town of Majalgaon. The structure measures 31.19 meters (102.3 feet) in height from its foundation and spans a length of 6,488 meters (21,286 feet). The reservoir boasts a gross storage capacity of 453.64 million cubic meters.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Parli Vaijnath Temple (Jyotirlinga)" class="section">
            <h2>Parli Vaijnath Temple (Jyotirlinga)</h2>
            <img src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTEBTW_i0IbFkou2XMVLxZpfeuBrPlHNXa8zA&s" alt="Parli Vaijnath Temple (Jyotirlinga)" class="section-image">
            <p>The Shri Vaijnath Jyotirling Temple in Parli, Beed district, Maharashtra, is a revered Hindu pilgrimage site dedicated to Lord Shiva, and is considered one of India's twelve Jyotirlingas. The temple is also believed to have medicinal and spiritual powers, and is associated with legends of the elixir of immortality and the demon king Ravana. It is accessible by air, rail, and road, and offers various accommodation options. Visitors can also explore nearby attractions like Dharmapuri Fort and Yogeshwari Temple. While performing the rite of Abhishekam, male devotees are not allowed to wear clothes above the waist. The best time to visit is during the cooler months between September and February, or during festivals such as Mahashivratri and Shravan Maas.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Bindusara River Banks & Dam" class="section">
            <h2>Bindusara River Banks & Dam</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Bindusara River Banks & Dam" class="section-image">
            <p>The Bindusara River, also known as Bendsura, is a significant, though relatively small and seasonal, river in the Beed district of Maharashtra, India. It originates in the Balaghat Hills and flows through the city of Beed before joining the Sindphana River, which is a sub-tributary of the Godavari. The river is a vital water source for the city and surrounding areas, according to ResearchGate. Due to the region's rocky and undulating terrain, the Bindusara River is susceptible to violent floods during heavy rains, causing substantial damage and loss of life in the past. The most recent major flood occurred on July 23, 1989. In response to the river's pollution and flooding risk, the Beed district administration launched a cleaning drive, supported by various organizations, to remove plastic, garbage, and other litter from the river. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kapildhar Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Kapildhar Waterfall</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Kapildhar Waterfall" class="section-image">
            <p>Kapildhar waterfall, located near Beed in Maharashtra, is a popular tourist destination known for its natural beauty and tranquility. The waterfall is situated in a picturesque setting amidst mountains and forests and cascades down a height of approximately 60 feet. The location is ideal for nature lovers and offers a peaceful escape with a serene environment. There's also a temple dedicated to Manmath Swami and Lord Shiva located near the waterfall. Visitors can reach the waterfall via a short trek and enjoy the beauty of the surrounding lush greenery and the impressive waterfall, especially during the monsoon season. Wheelchair accessibility options are available including an entrance and parking lot. However, visitors have pointed out a lack of maintenance and sanitation facilities</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Dharur Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Dharur Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Dharur Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Dharur Fort, also known as Mahadurga, is a historical fort located in Dharur, Beed district, Maharashtra, India. Originally called Mahadurga, it was rebuilt in 1567 AD by Kishwar Khan Lari, a Sardar of Adilshah, using the stones from the ancient fort. This fortified structure boasts strong walls reminiscent of Rajasthani forts and features structures like Hawa Mahal, Rani Mahal, Hathi Burj, Shah Burj, and Takshal Burj within its premises. Located near Dharur village, the fort offers stunning views of the surrounding hills and greenery. It is accessible by car and is known for being family-friendly, with wheelchair-accessible entrances and parking. Dharur Fort is open from 9 AM to 5 PM daily and holds a rating of 4.3 based on 685 user reviews on Google Maps. Visitors can also explore nearby attractions such as Dharur Fort Lake, Rajuri Ves, and Bidusara Dam. Efforts are reportedly underway to renovate and preserve the fort. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Balaji Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Balaji Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Balaji Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Multiple Balaji temples can be found in the Beed district of Maharashtra, India, each holding its own significance and attracting devotees seeking blessings. The Shree Balaji Bhagwan Temple in Majalgaon is a notable example, highly rated by visitors for its spiritual atmosphere and cleanliness. Another Balaji Temple, also located near Majalgaon, is praised for its neatness and peaceful ambiance, drawing crowds for its divine idol. The Beed Wale Balaji in Balaji Nagar, Beed, is another temple dedicated to Lord Balaji, although currently without user reviews. Balaji temples are generally revered as important centers for worshiping Lord Hanuman, who is believed to be a powerful deity capable of granting wishes and providing protection. Beyond Beed, other Balaji temples like the famous Mehandipur Balaji Temple in Rajasthan are known for their healing and exorcism practices. When planning a visit, it's advised to check temple timings and any specific rituals or festivals that may be taking place, as these can vary depending on the temple.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
